<subsection xml:id="subsec-translation">
    <title>Translation</title>
    <p>
        In geometry, translation is a rigid transformation that moves every point of a shape or object by the same 
        distance in a given direction, without changing its size, shape, or orientation.
    </p>
    <p>
        <term>Key Properties of Translation:</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Preserves size and shape → The original and translated figures are congruent.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Maintains orientation → The figure does not rotate or reflect.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Follows a translation vector → The movement is defined by a specific <m>(x, y)</m> shift, such as <m>(3, -2)</m> 
                    meaning "move 3 units right and 2 units down." 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Exploring Translations on a Cartesian Plane
            </p>
            <p>
                <term>Materials needed</term>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Graph paper  
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Ruler and pencils 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           Colored pens for distinguishing original and translated figures 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            On a Cartesian plane, plot the following points: <m>A(2,3), B(2,7), C(6,7), D(6,3). </m> 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Connect the points to form a quadrilateral. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Apply translation to the figure using the translation vector <m>\mathbf{v} = (3, -2).</m>
                             Apply the translation rule <m>(x,y) \to (x+3, y-2)</m> to each point. For example, applying the translation to point <m>A(2,3)</m> 
                             the new coordinate for <m>A</m> which will be called <m>A'</m> will be: <m>A(2,3) \to A'(2+3,3-2) = A'(5, 1).</m> 
                             Similarly, determine the new coordinates for the translated quadrilateral <m>B', C' \text{ and } D'.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Plot the new points and connect them to form the translated quadrilateral. Use a different color to differentiate the original and translated shapes. 
                            Label the new points accordingly: <m>A', B', C', D'.</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            With your fellow learners: Compare the original figure with the translated image, discuss how the translation affected the position of the shape 
                            and verify that distances and angles remained unchanged.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The vetices of a triangle are given as follows: <m>A(-1,1), B(-4,2), C(-2,4).</m> Plot the points on a coordinate plane and connect them to form a triangle. 
                 Applying a translation vector <m>\mathbf{v} = (4, 2)</m>, determine the new coordinates of the translated triangle and plot it on your cartesian plane.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Applying the translation rule to each coordinates of the triangle we get the new coordinates of the translated image as:
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>A(-1,1) \to A'(-1+4,1+2) = A'(3,3)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>B(-4,2) \to B'(-4+4,2+2) = B'(0,4)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>C(-2,4) \to A'(-2+4,4+2) = C'(2,6)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
              The triangle and its translated image on a coordinate appear as shown:  
            </p>
            <image>
                <latex-image label="transation-triangle">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    
                    % Draw axes
                    \draw[-&gt;] (-7,0) -- (7,0) node[right] {\textbf{x-axis}};
                    \draw[-&gt;] (0,-7) -- (0,7) node[above] {\textbf{y-axis}};

                    % Draw the grid lines
                    \draw[step=1,gray,very thin] (-7,-7) grid (7,7);

                    % Grid and labels
                    \foreach \x in {-6,-5,-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5,6} {
                        \draw[thick] (\x,-0.1) -- (\x,0.1); % Tick marks on x-axis
                        \node[anchor=north] at (\x,-0.2) {\textbf{\x}};
                    }
    
                    \foreach \y in {-6,-5,-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4,5,6} {
                        \draw[thick] (-0.1,\y) -- (0.1,\y); % Tick marks on y-axis
                        \node[anchor=east] at (-0.2,\y) {\textbf{\y}};
                    }
                    
                    % Plot original point A, B, C
                    \fill[red] (-1,1) circle (3pt) node[above] {\textbf{A(-1,1)}};
                    \fill[red] (-4,2) circle (3pt) node[above] {\textbf{B(-4,2)}};
                    \fill[red] (-2,4) circle (3pt) node[above] {\textbf{C(-2,4)}};
                    
                    % Plot the triangle
                    \draw[thick, red] (-1,1) -- (-4,2) -- (-2,4) -- cycle;
                    \fill[red, opacity=0.4] (-1,1) -- (-4,2) -- (-2,4) -- cycle;

                    % Plot translated point A', B' and C'
                    \fill[green] (3,3) circle (3pt) node[above] {\textbf{A'(3,3)}};
                    \fill[green] (0,4) circle (3pt) node[above] {\textbf{B'(0,4)}};
                    \fill[green] (2,6) circle (3pt) node[above] {\textbf{C'(2,6)}};

                    % Plot the translated image
                    \draw[thick, green] (3,3) -- (0,4) -- (2,6) -- cycle;
                    \fill[green, opacity=0.4] (3,3) -- (0,4) -- (2,6) -- cycle;
                    
                
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
</subsection>